statement_to_voters:
I'm determined to win this seat for Labour and stand up for the people of Central Ayrshire.



I was born and brought up in the constituency and live here too. I did my public service overseas as British Trade Commissioner for South Asia securing billions of pounds of investment that created thousands of jobs in Scotland and the UK. With the Scottish Whisky Association for example, I secured a major reduction in whisky tarrifs in India - resulting in many more bottles sold and safeguarding jobs here in Scotland. Now I'd like to use my experience to represent the community where I grew up in Parliament.



Having spoken to thousands of voters across Central Ayrshire since I was selected, it's clear are people are fed up with the SNP and the Tories. Only Scottish Labour can beat the SNP here and only a Labour Government can deliver for the people of Central Ayrshire. If elected, I will:



Tackle the cost of living crisis, cut household bills and put money back in your pocket;



Fight for better local services suffering eye-watering cuts from SNP- and Tory-led councils ;



Stand up for our local health services and support Labour's plans for an NHS fit for the future;



Work to create new high-quality jobs, a genuine living wage and opportunities for people here; and



Promote our high streets and local businesses and bring pride back to our town centres.

Gwent Police is a failing organisation. Its multiple failures have seen it lose the confidence of the public. Its canteen culture has seen numerous police investigated for gross misconduct, a revolving door of people resigning before they can be sacked. There have been calls for it to be put into special measures or subject to an independent investigation. The force is still subject to a number of ongoing investigations, including one into the toxic culture revealed in text messages given to The Times newspaper. There was a damning Police Inspectorate report in 2023, revealing multiple failures in the force.

But you do not need Police watchdogs and media to realise Gwent Police is failing, you can use your eyes.  My own inner city ward in Newport was a quiet safe area a decade ago, but now it feels abandoned by the police. When issues are raised the response from the police is arrogant and condescending.

If elected I would make sure:

•   The new Chief Constable is recruited from outside the force;

•   We return to community policing, talking to the public rather than hiding from them. Encourage Neighbourhood Watch schemes;

•   We investigate all crimes, experience has shown dealing with minor crime reduces all crime;

•   Senior management needs shaking up, see the 2023 Inspectorate report;

•   Recruitment vetting needs to be fit for purpose, we do not want any Wayne Couzens here;

•   Consider reopening police station front desks, we need the police and public to be in direct contact;

•   Sort out the 101 phone number mess, it is currently not fit for purpose;

•   Put more resources into solving crime, Gwent Police’s conviction rate is a joke

Address prepared by Michael O’Carroll (Agent), at 12 Jackson Place, Newport, NP19 8FR.

County Councillor for past 8 years. County Group manifesto headed by tacking climate emergency and making government more open and transparent. Invest in youth services and close attainment gap in education
 
As Police & Crime Commissioner I would:
Emphasise improved detection rates – For years Thames Valley did not solve enough crimes;  
Ensure support for victims of crime is funded and not cut; 
Protect front line policing including officers on the beat;
Work with other agencies to ensure cases are progressed to court as quickly as possible;
Consult the public, community groups and elected representatives including town and parish councils about local policing priorities;
Listen to young people who cannot vote, but need a say about both crime and policing issues;
Ensure value for money – but protect services to the public.
Thames Valley is a very large police area, the largest non-urban police force in England. It ranges from sparsely populated rural areas in the Chilterns, Cotswolds and Berkshire Downs to urban centres such as Slough, Reading, Newbury, Oxford, Banbury, Bicester, Aylesbury, High Wycombe, Milton Keynes and many other towns and villages.
